<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<a href="grammar-particle-de.html">@HI{{de}}</a> also expresses a reason or cause, however,
it can only be used with nouns whereas @HI{{@EM{{node}}}} (and @HI{{kara}}) are only used with sentences.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{node}}}} and @HI{{kara}} have similar meanings but @HI{{kara}} does not imply that
the speaker believes that the subordinate clause is the reason or cause for the main clause.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{kara}}, and not @HI{{@EM{{node}}}}, must be used when:
<ul>
<li> the subordinate clause involves conjecture
<li> the subordinate clause involves volition or personal opinion
<li> the main clause involves a command, request, suggestion or invitation
</ul>
</p>

<p>
In @S1{{}}@HI{{@EM{{node}}}}@S2{{}}, @HI{{@EM{{node}}}} can be replaced by @HI{{keredo(mo)}}, although the reverse does not always hold.
</p>

